# Approval sidecar secrets (cp env.example .env -- gitignored). This is the ONLY
# container that holds the approval-channel credentials; tools never see them.
#
# Which platform delivers the Approve/Deny card. Implemented: slack (default).
# Planned: discord, telegram. SECURITY NOTE for the telegram provider: it must
# not be used while the telegram TOOL is deployed -- that tool operates your own
# account (reads chats, presses inline buttons), so any card your account can
# see, the model can approve itself.
#APPROVAL_PROVIDER=slack
#
# Slack app setup (once, at https://api.slack.com/apps):
#  1. OAuth & Permissions -> scope `chat:write` -> install to workspace -> copy the
#     Bot User OAuth Token (xoxb-...) into SLACK_BOT_TOKEN.
#  2. Basic Information -> copy the Signing Secret into SLACK_SIGNING_SECRET.
#  3. Interactivity & Shortcuts -> ON -> Request URL:
#        https://approval.<MCP_DOMAIN>/slack/interact
#     (ONE URL for the whole stack -- this sidecar answers clicks for every tool.)
#  4. Make a (private) channel, invite the bot, put its channel ID in
#     SLACK_APPROVAL_CHANNEL.
#
# The Slack values are REQUIRED for approvals to work: the card is the only
# channel that reaches the human (no link goes to the chat -- it reads as prompt
# injection there). Without them, gated tools report the approval as undeliverable.
SLACK_BOT_TOKEN=
SLACK_SIGNING_SECRET=
SLACK_APPROVAL_CHANNEL=
# Public base for the approval page linked from the Slack card (fallback if the
# buttons fail); the tunnel overlay stamps this from MCP_DOMAIN -- set it here
# only when running outside compose.
#APPROVAL_PUBLIC_URL=https://approval.<MCP_DOMAIN>
